data.description: Knight Connections 2026: R U My Roommate? Looking for a roommate for next year—or just want better vibes in your housing journey? 👀Knight Connections: R U My Roommate? is a fun, low-pressure event designed to help you meet new people, explore what you need in a roommate, and build real connections across Rutgers. Move through interactive stations like Boundary Bingo, Tidy Truth or Dare, Red Flag Room, and the fan-favorite LEGO Flower Exchange 🌸. Along the way, you’ll reflect on lifestyle habits, communication styles, and shared-living expectations—all while earning raffle entries for IKEA prizes, swag, and more. Whether you leave with a potential roommate, a new friend, or just more clarity about what you want, Knight Connections is here to help you start the housing process with confidence (and fun). 🗓 Choose one or both nights to attend:📍 Monday, 1/27 — Druskin Lounge, Honors College (College Ave)📍 Tuesday, 1/28 — Livingston B Reading Room (behind RU Cinema)⏰ 8:00 PM – 10:00 PM (both nights) ✨ Open to first-year, transfer, and returning students✨ Complete stations → earn raffle entries✨ No pressure. data.description: What does it mean to survive—intellectually, politically, ecologically, or aesthetically—in a moment defined by crisis? When uncertainty and chaos prevail, those who endure must bend, not break. They must adapt, redirect, stay fluid. How do figures of water help us think survival not as a static state but as a process: precarious, contingent, always at risk of being swept under? Survival and water: two conceptual forces that converge in literary, philosophical, and political discourses across the German tradition. Whether in the form of biblical floods, rising oceans, or mythic rivers—water stages a sight of duality: It is where life and death, healing and destruction, calmness and acceleration are able to meet in a resistant stream of becoming. To survive—especially “with one’s head above water”—is to inhabit the threshold between endurance and submersion, grasping for breath, clarity, meaning. At the same time, survival carries its own paradoxes: Who survives and at what cost? What kinds of knowledge or expression survive catastrophe, exile, war, or erasure—and which are drowned out? Water leaks across genres and disciplines: as metaphor for time and memory, as site of passage and peril, as resource and threat, as a medium of cleansing, forgetting, or border-policing. Meanwhile, survival speaks equally to historical trauma and everyday precarity, to climate catastrophe and cultural memory, to the bodies that wash ashore and those that remain submerged in the archive. This conference seeks contributions that take up the dual themes of survival and water—literally, figuratively, or formally—as critical frameworks. We welcome engagements with water as metaphor, medium, matter, and menace, and with survival as a philosophical problem, a narrative form, or a historical condition. What does it mean to be in over one’s head—psychically, politically, or ecologically? How might “keeping one’s head above water” register both resistance and exhaustion? How are the concepts of water and survival marshaled by thinkers, writers, artists, or regimes? How do literature, film, and theory reckon with flood, immersion, drowning, or breath? What kinds of bodies are asked to stay afloat, and at what cost? Brief: how do we keep our head above water; how do we survive the current?
data.name: HEAD ABOVE WATER: Surviving the Current. Rutgers German Graduate Student Conference

data.description: Come join us on Sunday, April 19, for Haru's biggest event of the semester, Spring 2026 Showcase! Our goal is to share Korean pop culture through the art of dance. This event is open to everyone: general members, families, Rutgers students, and non-Rutgers students! Our showcase is our biggest event, where our members get to showcase a multitude of K-pop performances they’ve been preparing for months for our audience. There are two acts with an intermission, which includes a raffle with a bunch of prizes our audience can partake in and possibly win big! And the best part is that admission is FREE for all!  You don't have to be performing to attend, so come out and support our performers! ♡ Let's cheer each other on and enjoy each other's company! You may also get some sweet treats, snacks, and refreshments from us to enjoy while watching performances 👀 Our showcase is also livestreamed on our YouTube page for audience members who cannot attend in person, but would love to support our performers! If you're watching from online, thank you for supporting Haru Dance ♡ More information on parking will be detailed here later in the semester. Contact us directly on IG: @harudance_official or Email: haru.kdcc@gmail.com if you have any questions! Can't wait to see y'all soon!
